## Finding: Toolkit Has No Prompt Injection Defense or AI Security Hardening (OWASP LLM Top 10 Deviation)

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: OWASP has published the LLM Top 10 vulnerabilities (2025): LLM01 Prompt Injection, LLM02 Insecure Output Handling, LLM03 Training Data Poisoning, LLM04 Model Denial of Service, LLM06 Sensitive Information Disclosure, LLM07 Insecure Plugin Design. The toolkit is the AI layer of this framework — it defines HOW AI tools are used. Yet NO toolkit skill addresses: prompt injection in AI-assisted workflows (malicious code in files read by Claude could inject into the AI's context), insecure output handling (AI-generated code used directly without validation), sensitive information disclosure (API keys, PII in prompts sent to external AI), insecure plugin/MCP design (the ai_tool_orchestration skill lists MCP servers but has NO security guidance for them). The ai_tool_orchestration skill says "Only connect MCP servers you trust" with no further guidance — a dangerously thin treatment of a high-severity risk.
### Proposed Resolution: New SKILL.md named "ai-security-hardening" in toolkit phase. Trigger commands: "AI security review", "harden AI pipeline", "OWASP LLM audit". Scope: Covers the OWASP LLM Top 10 in the context of this framework's AI tool usage — prompt injection prevention, output validation gates, sensitive data scrubbing before API calls, and secure MCP server configuration. Priority P0 — this is a security gap in the AI layer itself.
### Cross-Phase Impact: All phases. Particularly critical: Build (Claude reads production code), Secure (AI analyzes sensitive security findings), Handoff (documentation with sensitive system details).

